title: For Sale:  For Sale
postcontent:
Makarov is not on the list of manufacturers so the closest weapon to it is a Walther PPK.

Makarov pistol is acknowledged to be one of the best 20th century pistols in the world, along side with Browning, Walter, Beretta, and Astra. Mak’s serial production has been going on for over 50 years on mechanical factory in the city of Izhevsk, Russia.

During that time, entire family of weapons were derived from Makarov. They are gas, pneumatic and models made specifically for export. They all have wide spectrum of application that vary from military, law enforcement and secret service down to sporting and casual practice shooting.

Makarov is currently the only pistol in the world that successfully passes so called “combined conditions” testing. That test consists of field trials in dirt, rain, snow. Combination of qualities such as size, weight, magazine capacity, barrel energy, recoil and cost makes Makarov a leader amongst majority of handguns available on the market even today.

Izhevsk factory produces three export caliber flavors: 9x18 Makarov, 9x17 Kurtz, 9x19 Parabellum. All modifications of pistols can have either fixed or adjustable sights. Magazine capacities are 8 or 12 rounds for 9x17 and 9x18, and 8 for 9x19. These models come in two possible finishes - oxidated and nickel-plated. There is also a .380 ACP version of Makarov which is very rare and was supposedly never shipped to the states. 

There is also a .380-ACP version of Makarov that is exclusively sold by "B-West" company. 
Mine is a "B-West" edition and stamped as such. Also. it has the adjustable sights.

The one I am selling is the .380 ACP oxidated and Blued (made in Russia). It fires both 9x17 and .380 Ammo. It has the larger non-slip rubberized grips and the 19 lb. recoil spring for better accuracy when using 9x17 kurtz ammunition.

I have used up to 115 grain ammunition in this pistol since I put the 19lb. recoil spring in it without any issues, and they make a .380 round that has a 17 inch penetration depth, so if you think that it will not get the job done, you are "DEAD" wrong!

postcontent:
For sale is a Federal Ordinance M1A (Serial No. on Request) probably manufactured in 1984. 

ALL Chinese parts have been replaced with US GI parts !!!

It has a 21” after-market National Match (NM) Barrel with a NM front blade sight, a NM hooded aperture (peep) rear sight with ½ minute adjustments. The wooden stock is in good condition and has been modified with fiberglass reinforcing and a “multi-cam” finish, with a modified fore-end fitted with a short section of picatinny rail in front of the stud swivel. 

The stock also features the classic butt stock cleaning kit space (kit not included) with swing-up shoulder plate. There are some slight dings and mars to the camo finish on the stock but it is in good serviceable condition. The bore is clean with no visible corrosion or blemishes, the rifling is shiny and well grooved. 

NOTE:  The Chinese parts inherent in many later Fed Ord models have been replaced with GI gear, with the exception of the bolt only - which was US made anyway.

The action has some machine imperfections and slight wear on the bolt channel but this is standard on many pieces and does not in the least way effect shot precision or function. Overall it is a great and highly accurate shooter with the exceptional trigger break expected from a good condition M1A. I have four (4) 20 rd magazines, two (2) 30 rd magazines and one (1) 5 rd magazine (for hunting). 

I also have a spare modified "project" stock and a parts kit containing: (1) connector lock pin, a magazine catch pin, a gas cylinder plug, an Op Rod spring guide, an extractor spring w/plunger, a safety spring, and a gas cylinder lock (milled, USGI).
